
<!--
  nav2_minimal_tree.xml — the behaviour tree bt_navigator runs for every
  NavigateToPose goal shuttle_manager sends.  It is the "what to do, and what to
  do when it goes wrong" layer of the navigation stack: PipelineSequence =
  normal driving (plan + follow); RecoveryNode wraps it so a failure triggers
  the fallback (back up + wait) and retries, up to 6 times.

  Replan the global path at 2 Hz (RateController) so a newly-seen obstacle is
  routed around quickly; the controller (collision-check ON) follows it and
  stops if something is on the path.

  IMPORTANT: NO ClearEntireCostmap anywhere.  Clearing the costmap deletes every
  marked obstacle (the SLAM-mapped ones AND live ones), so after a clear the
  robot replans on a blank map and drives straight through obstacles it was
  avoiding (observed: it "forgot" a book it had been avoiding and ran it over).
  The obstacle layer already clears cells that the lidar sees become free
  (raytracing), so a removed obstacle still disappears normally — we just never
  wipe everything.  On failure we only back up a little and wait, then retry,
  WITHOUT forgetting obstacles.
-->
<root main_tree_to_execute="MainTree">
  <BehaviorTree ID="MainTree">
    <RecoveryNode number_of_retries="6" name="NavigateRecovery">
      <PipelineSequence name="NavigateWithReplanning">
        <RateController hz="2.0">
          <ComputePathToPose goal="{goal}" path="{path}" planner_id="GridBased"/>
        </RateController>
        <FollowPath path="{path}" controller_id="FollowPath"/>
      </PipelineSequence>
      <ReactiveFallback name="RecoveryFallback">
        <GoalUpdated/>
        <RoundRobin name="RecoveryActions">
          <BackUp backup_dist="0.15" backup_speed="0.05"/>
          <Wait wait_duration="2.0"/>
        </RoundRobin>
      </ReactiveFallback>
    </RecoveryNode>
  </BehaviorTree>
</root>
